## G.30 Deep-seed — a full worked debug session

Let me walk a real bug scenario end-to-end.

You have a cart that plays a sound when the player earns a point. The sound plays sometimes but not always. You do not know why.

**Introspect the suspect verb.**

```scheme
(help 'play-sound)
;; => (:name \"play-sound\" :perm \"animate\" :powerTier \"animate\" ...)
```

The verb requires `animate` power tier. That is a substrate power gate.

**Check the substrate.**

```scheme
(substrate-power-tier)
;; => 'quarter
```

The substrate is at quarter power. Verbs with `powerTier animate` are skipped at quarter tier.

**Bug found.** The substrate throttles animate verbs when it drops to quarter power. Your sound skips when the runtime is under load.

**Fix.** Either raise the substrate power (if you control it) or use a verb with `powerTier paint` for sounds that must always play.

Total: three introspection calls. No debugger. No print statements. Bug diagnosed and fixed in under a minute.

That is the debug story Motoi's introspection layer enables. The rest of the recipes in this appendix are variations on this shape.

## G.31 Deep-seed — trace with tracing off

Sometimes you cannot enable trace (production, performance concerns). You still have Cortex.

Record specific state at specific points via `cortex/record`. After the run, `cortex/query` gives you the trace.

```scheme
(define (checkpoint name value)
  (cortex/record
    :subject 'debug
    :predicate name
    :object value
    :at (current-second)
    :source 'checkpoint))

;; sprinkle throughout your code
(checkpoint 'input input)
(checkpoint 'after-transform x)
(checkpoint 'result result)
```

After the run:

```scheme
(cortex/query :subject 'debug :order-by 'at)
;; => chronological log of every checkpoint
```

A poor-man's trace built from Cortex. Works when regular tracing does not.

## G.32 The truly final observation

Introspection makes debugging faster. Not because it does the work for you; because it eliminates the guessing. Every step is grounded in a value the runtime returned. No inference, no assumption, no hope.

That's the difference between hoping the bug is where you think it is and knowing where it is. Introspection gives you the second.

Onward to Appendix H.

## G.33 One last thought

Every recipe in this appendix started as a habit someone else invented. If you invent a new recipe, share it. Every named recipe compounds the community's debugging speed.

Onward to Appendix H — the composer round-trip demonstration that closes the book.

## G.34 A last worked case, briefly

You suspect a Cortex read returns stale data. Recipe:

1. `(cortex/query :subject 's :order-by 'at)` — see all records chronologically.
2. Note the most recent :at value.
3. `(current-second)` — see now.
4. If the difference is large, the record is stale by that much.

Three calls. You know exactly how stale the data is.

