## G.36 Deep-seed — a common mistake to avoid

Do not skip step 1 of the general reflex. Binding the suspicious value to a name is critical because otherwise you cannot re-introspect it. Without a binding, each subsequent call reproduces the entire computation, which changes state (if the code has side effects) or wastes time.

```scheme
;; BAD — re-runs my-verb multiple times
(type-of (my-verb input))
(length (my-verb input))
(keys (my-verb input))

;; GOOD — runs once, introspects the result many times
(define r (my-verb input))
(type-of r)
(length r)
(keys r)
```

Small habit, big payoff.

## G.37 Deep-seed — the two-fingers rule

For debugging at the REPL: keep two fingers on the introspection primitives, always. `describe` and `type-of` should be the fastest thing you can type.

When something surprises you, do not think — introspect. The thinking comes after the data is on stdout.

Two fingers. Instant reaches. Fast debugging.

