## G.40 A closing observation on the reflex

Debugging is a discipline. Introspection is the tool. The recipes are the vocabulary. The reflex is the fluency.

Master the recipes, and debugging becomes fast. Master the reflex, and debugging becomes automatic. Master both, and you become a debugger other people ask for help.

## G.41 Deep-seed — one more scenario

You have a cart that intermittently fails to publish. Sometimes it works, sometimes it errors with `perm-denied`.

Recipe G.24 (heisenbug) plus recipe G.4 (wrong-perm):

1. Trace the publish verb. `,trace card/publish`.
2. Run the cart until it fails.
3. `(error-context (last-error))` — read the perm requirement and caller tier at failure time.
4. Compare to a successful run's trace entry.
5. What differs? Often the substrate power tier or the confirm flag.

Two recipes composed. Bug diagnosed.

## G.42 The truly final note

Debugging in Motoi is a joy compared to debugging in most languages. Not because Motoi has fewer bugs — every language has bugs — but because introspection makes bugs shallower.

A shallow bug is one you can see the source of quickly. A deep bug is one where the trail goes cold. Introspection keeps trails from going cold. Every step is grounded in a returned value.

That is the closing observation. Now onward to Appendix H.

